            "answer_text": "A2A Work harder and smarter, or\u2026 Lots of advice in the world about working harder \u2014 spending more time studying, less time on things that keep you from studying or use up brain cells for chemical recreation, getting a study group together or hiring a tutor, etc. If lack of effort is the problem, they can help. I always advise working smarter. Talk to your teachers! Let them know you care about doing better and listen to their advice on how to focus on what they want to see for the grade. If they are creating their own tests, learn what parts of the material they tend to focus on for exams. If they are using exams from the textbook company, pay attention to section headings and any review questions in the book. The grade game is about giving the grader what they want to see. You can study until you have deep understanding of most of the material and still get a bad grade if you miss the part the teacher is looking for you to show. My lowest grade when earning my doctorate was in a course I took in the evening 3 hours from home and work. I could barely make it there in time for class and then would get after midnight. The problem was that the prof made heavy use of materials they put on reserve to read at the campus library and I could not get there. I went to the local professional library for the same subject and worked hard. But, there would always be some part that was in her materials and not in what I found on my own. I learned a lot from her and invited her to the celebration when I passed the final exams on my dissertation. But, the point is that I failed to get the grade I wanted because my studying was not matching exactly what she expected to see in the responses. Grades are about giving them exactly what THEY want to see, not what we as students think is important. See if there is a way to know your teachers better and focus your work on what they want. The or? If you work as hard as you can, work as smart as you can, and still get low grades\u2026start planning your future accordingly. And, I DO NOT mean the smart aleck, \u201cGet ready to dip fries for a living.\u201d Some people wisely choose a high paying trade that matches their ability to do things instead of academic work which does not match their best way to perform. But, some just need more time working on the foundational material and do well at a community college, then decide whether a degree from there will get them where they want to go or else transfer to a better university when they are ready. Sometimes we are asking people to learn things at an age (even in high school) their brain development is just not ready for and there is nothing wrong with the student. Some people find that mathematics that refused to make sense in high school becomes much easier to learn in their twenties. Best of luck whichever plan fits you! ",
