            },
            "answer_text": "I struggled with some subjects in high school. Finally, I figured some things out. I realized why I was very good in my favorite subject. I used the skills in that subject and applied them to my weak subjects. I accecpted help. Sometimes I just needed things explained in a way the teacher could not express. Sometimes learning from a peer was easier than learning from a professional. I started from scratch. This was very simple, yet very difficult. I began from the beginning of the textbook reading the introduction. I had a fresh notebook in front of me. I read carefully, and took careful notes. These notes were for me so I used methods that made sense to my brain. I did every end-of-chapter task. I began to grasp the subject. I kept doing this every free minute until I was caught up to the class. It meant that I did my chores, my schoolwork, and nothing else. What got me through it was knowing this would not be forever. One of the most important things I learned was understanding how my brain liked to learn. I also learned that if I was not comfortable with a subject by the second week of class, that was when I needed to ask for help; for me, things would not improve on their own. I learned the \u201csky would not fall;\u201d although life would not be fun if I messed up, I could learn to adjust and to cope with difficulties. ",
