                "name": "Jan Dawson",
                "href": "/profile/Jan-Dawson-3"
            },
            "answer_text": "Apparently, your parents aren't involved with your studies. The teachers are a good place to start. They know of your poor grades. Haven't they talked or mentioned anything to you? If not, you could mention that you need help. Your guidance councelsor should be involved. Have you talked to him? The basic questions are: are you reading and thinking and then understanding the material presented in class, are you doing the homework assignments, taking notes, paying attention in class, asking questions? Also, not everyone can get terrific grades, either. It takes effort-- and sometimes even with effort you may just get by. Instead of trying to tackle all of this at once, ask one teacher\u2014 the one that seems that would help you the most \u2014 and ask if she could set aside 10 minutes to discuss a strategy or a step-by-step process to help you improve your grades. You can walk a thousand miles simply by taking the first step. A2A ",
